<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>10th January 2013</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Manlove Forensics Limited (FSS013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Declaration of interest:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This submission represents the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">sole </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">view of Manlove Forensics Ltd, based in South Oxfordshire, near Wantage.  Our company is one of the smaller suppliers of forensic science services to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Criminal Justice System (CJS). </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our company is entirely owned and run by its two founding directors.  We cover a wide range of evidence types but those that we provide to Police are mainly in relation to footwear and firearms evidence as well as a number of specialist ecological services.  Our staff are highly experienced and all our scientists have been working within the CJS since before the FSS closure.  We feel we are well placed to address the issues which you have requested a response.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Does the Government have an effective strategy for forensic science in the UK and is it sufficient to support forensic science R&amp;D and criminal justice?</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">At present we are not clear on what the Government’s strategy is in relation to forensic science within the UK.  We know that cost saving is of great importance but we do not see an overarching end-point.  Presently significant quantities of work</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> which were previously performed by Forensic Science Providers (FSPs)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are being ‘insourced’ by Police-run laboratories, in Force.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is a strict requirement that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">providers on the National Framework have attained accreditation to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ISO 17025 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">standard in order to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> undertake Police work</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and we agree with this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. For small providers such as ourselves this represents a significant cost and is a challenging bench-mark to reach and retain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘In-sourcing is seen as a threat to impartiality and to a stable forensic market’. More critically, in-sourcing causes an investigation to be fragmented which has implications to the CJS. It </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">can also</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> contradict best practice, increase lost opportunities and potentially </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">could lead to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">miscarriages of justice. CPS holds the view that fragmentation of work does not have a significant effect on their role. This might be true, but there is a risk that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">implications of this approach, scientifically,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> not fully understood. In real terms it means that the person finding and recovering the body fluid stain, for example, from an item of clothing; does not see or deal with the DNA result that is generated from it. When the two are divorced, it is extremely difficult for the reporting scientist</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to provide an opinion as to what body fluid the DNA came from and then to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">robustly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">evaluate how the body fluid was </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">initially </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">deposited</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">his is further complicated when we are dealing with multi-evidence types. It is not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the case</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that all items from one investigation are sent to a single laboratory and certainly not true that this happens for all ‘serious crime’ as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> be asserted.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> We have experienced situations where subsequent submissions have been sent to different providers and of exhibits</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> within those submissions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> having been processed and reported by several independent reporting officers within those providers. Continuity and efficiency is lost and there is a lack of overall professional insight.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">At present, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">although </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">there is no mandatory requirement for a company to undertake </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">research </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and development activities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, as a provider to the national framework we have an obligation to undertake research and a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ctively seek to collaborate with academic institutions and provide inputs on a wide range of university courses and CPD programs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">here is little incentive to perform research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is there </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a tangible </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">incentive to publish and share such data </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">if it provides a competitive advantage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our experience is that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">whilst undergraduate and MSc projects are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">well-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">supported, there is little appetite</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, or funding,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for PhD studies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">implications of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">abstraction </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to supervise </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">such studies can be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">significant and un- remunerated</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">We would respectfully request that the committee consider that although Forensic Science is an amalgamation of many different sciences, that the research funding bodies re-evaluate their classification of Forensic Science to lessen the risk of worthwhile projects being unsupported.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Did the FSS transition and closure run smoothly and within budget?</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The FSS closure resulted in a huge loss of experienced personnel from Forensic Science in the UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the perceived cost of this is massive, not least of all the loss of intellectual wealth</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  It was expected that staff would move to private companies but in practise, the majority have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">not been able to secure equivalent jobs or have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">chosen to leave, for a variety of reasons, disillusionment being one the most common that we have encountered. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> We</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> think it’s impossible to put a price on the loss of expertise that occurred in 2010-11.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Although the Committee stated </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">previously </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that the Forensic Transition Board must ensure that forensic scientists employed by the FSS are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> retained within the profession</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in reality </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the majority</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of forensic practitioners have</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in fact</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> exited the discipline. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Recruitment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">within FSPs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">now mainly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">fuelled by short-term demand to provide analytical se</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rvices, not evaluative science, and as a consequence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">providers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are offering largely short-term contracts in response to this.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">For example, d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">uring</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the closure of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">London Laboratory of the FSS in the region of 100 scientific staff were </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">transfer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">red </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">under TUPE to the Metropolitan Police Forensics Division. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Staff loss</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> included ~</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">20 reporting scientists from the Sexual Offences team </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">who were excluded </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">because </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">xual o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ffence casework</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">was to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">be outsourced</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> These scientists, who </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">we</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">re extremely experienced, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">had </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">competencies in a wide range of forensic applications: strategy setting, examination of items for body fluids, assessment and interpretation of blood patterns, complex interpretation and court reporting</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">all of which are arguably transferable to any violent crime investigation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> were made redundant</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is our experience that very little of these staff, a trend which is reflective of losses throughout the country, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">have been</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">dopted into the remaining FSP’s. I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n fact many </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">providers selected to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">increase their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">scientific </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">capability with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> new recruits</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> or apprentices</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, including</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">graduates who we</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">re cheaper to employ </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> require extensive training. Currently, it takes approximately a year to train a junior forensic biologist; significantly longer for them to be ready to go to court. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What impacts have the FSS’s closure had on (i) the criminal justice system and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(ii) forensic science R&amp;D and tr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">aining? In particular, have the appropriate quality standards and accreditation been rigorously maintained? (please provide evidence/examples)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In our view, the possession of ISO 17025 is not, in itself</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> sufficient to maintain standards in Forensic Science and we continue to observe failures of standards when we conduct defence reviews, in addition to those that are publicised in the press. However, many of the police laboratories actively conducting forensic examinations continue to be unaccredited. This appears to present a double standard. It is also our understanding that a review is being undertaken by government into the requirements of police laboratories to adopt EU standards, amongst which was the mandatory requirement for laboratories to attain ISO 17025 accreditation. If this review concluded that this standard was not mandatory </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ould leave a two-tier system in operation and expose the CJS to risk. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">We would recommend that all laboratories carrying out forensic science work, including those that are Police based, work to the same Quality Standard with a clear road-map towards mandatory acceptance of such criteria.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Since the FSS closure, the number of staff available to the CJS has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">greatly reduced</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Of those retained, many have been subsumed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> into police laboratories in particular the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Evidence Recovery Unit </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">serving</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the Metropolitan Police. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Within this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> MPS-run </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">facility, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">scientists have found that the skills </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that they maintained in the FSS (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for example DNA reporting and interpretation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">have been lost and are being</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> replaced with other elements through retraining</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Whilst protecting jobs, this approach has further starved the forensic community of access to their expertise.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is little incentive for FSPs to train new staff members due to the numbers of scientists who are losing their positions.  For example, we understand that a major FSP is about to release </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a significant proportion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of their staff from their largest laboratory which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">will further reduce the intellectual wealth</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What should be role of the Forensic Science Regulator?</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Forensic Science Regulator should be a role with statutory powers and a remit that extends beyond setting Quality Standards.  At present, several FSPs, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">including ourselves</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> have support</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the role of the Forensic Science Regulator but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">understand that the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> role </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">was not defined to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">regulat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e the entire </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">market.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">For example, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">there is no regulation of defence scientists</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> exposing the CJS to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">potential</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There has been no replacement of CRFP with an equivalent body, which we feel is necessary.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e currently review a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> significant number of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cases and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in the last few years </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">have more recently seen a surge in the number of cases in which primary examinations are instructed on behalf of the defence. This is usually because scenarios have evolved, or additional information has come to light which has a bearing on the original examination strategy, but can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">often </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">because the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">examin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ation of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> an item </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">initially</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> was discounted simply on cost.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The submission of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">prima facia</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> evidence on behalf of the defence places the CJS in a very difficult situation a) because the submissions are not subject to the same disclosure rules as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">prosecution and b) because the findings of the defence are not subject to their own scientific review. This is unsatisfactory.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">We would recommend that scientists that act for the defence are also subject to regulation to ensure that the CJS is best served.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">We would also recommend that the remit of the Forensic Science Regulator is expanded and given statutory powers.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is the size of the forensics market and how stable is it?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We do not know the exact size of the forensic market but in our opinion it is ever shrinking.  For example, we were successful in winning a con</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tract from Operation Slingshot</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and were</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> provided </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">with forecast figures which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">meant</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> we needed to recruit a further member of staff</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. This</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">was done. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Police submissions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for this contract</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">currently run at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">25% of those predicted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> which is reflective of the fact that a larger proportion of the work has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">been taken ‘in-house’ to Police labo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ratories</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> than anticipates</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> We have calculated that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">if the forces</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">had </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘ou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t-sourced’ this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> work</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, as planned,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> there would be a considerable cost-saving; however they have no appetite to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">make those savings.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Forces across the UK have no pressure to operate under the same business models as FSPs.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Whilst there is continued uncertainty as to the actual size of the forensic market there also continues to be little transparency on actual </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in-sourced and out-sourced </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Police Force forensic spend. Because of t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">his the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">police customer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">has the potential to become the largest competitor to FSPs. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is no assurance, from the now majority providers of forensic services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that they will maintain their presence and in fact, at least one, has recently announced re-structuring which is expected to be associated with staff losses. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ithdrawal from the market would be catastrophic. There is little tangible support from the government to ensure that smaller providers are protected in the marketplace and it is a daunting prospect for independent providers to enter it at all. Loss/movement of work on such short timescales is unsustainable and doesn’t allow the market to settle. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How are forensic science services procured by police forces and could procurement processes be improved?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Forensic science services are procured using </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ramework </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">process </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and then through competitive tendering.  There </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a number of benchmarks to reach, which, once achieved, leaves price as effectively the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">major</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">basis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">on which contracts are awarded</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  At present all of the contractual terms are in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> favour of the Police customer; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">no guarantees </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are provided, or have to be provided, as to the actual v</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">olume</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of work that each successful provider will ultimately</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">receive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Although we recognise that crime levels fluctuate, we would expect that the proportions of outsourced works are proportionate.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">At present, the contracts awarded through the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">procurement f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ramework by Police are typically for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">three to four</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> years.  This timetable is particularly fragile and reduces the confidence that FSPs have to give staff full-time contracts for work and short-term tender specific contracts are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">mostly on offer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.  If the FSP aligns their staff to any particular contract, should the work ultimately transfer to another FSP during the next round of procurement, those staff are exposed to TUPE , which protects the employer from redundancy liability, but for the employee, can represent uncertainty in terms of both job and possible relocation at regular intervals. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">In terms of the current contracts, scientists have very little latitude in terms of deciding the strategy of a case.  The MG21, or submission form, completed by the customer, carries a list of products reflective of the examinations that are required</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, or authorised,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> on items submitted. Renegotiation for funding is required should the scientist believe a more appropriate strategy is best for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the case and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> can be refused.  Arguably this has removed one of the major pillars of independence of the forensic scientist.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-inden